│ 470   // with a non-constant difference, we shouldn't perform any pointer   │
│ 471   // grouping with those pointers. This is because we can easily get    │
│ 472   // into cases where the resulting check would return false, even when │
│ 473   // the accesses are safe.                                             │
│ 474   //                                                                    │
│ 475   // The following example shows this:                                  │
│ 476   // for (i = 0; i < 1000; ++i)                                         │
│ 477   //   a[5000 + i * m] = a[i] + a[i + 9000]                             │
│ 478   //                                                                    │
│ 479   // Here grouping gives a check of (5000, 5000 + 1000 * m) against     │
│ 480   // (0, 10000) which is always false. However, if m is 1, there is no  │
│ 481   // dependence. Not grouping the checks for a[i] and a[i + 9000]       │
│ allows                                                                      │
│ 482   // us to perform an accurate check in this case.                      │
│ 483   //                                                                    │
